  Hi Chon,
  Thanks for the thoughtful note, and for taking the time to review the pitch video.
  On open source, yes, definitely on the radar, though we have not launched it yet.
  Our current plan is to open source the piping and integration layer around LFX (our learning from experience library): trace capture, telemetry, reward and feedback ingestion, and clean interfaces
  into the surrounding stack. That gives developers something they can inspect, run locally, and plug into their own setup. The commercial offering is the managed improvement loop: harness tuning, model
   post-training and hosting where the setup allows it, and the regression checks and deployment controls needed to run those updates safely in production.
  So I do not see OSS and enterprise as opposing options. OSS is the bottoms up adoption wedge. Enterprise is where the highest value workflows, reward signals, and budgets are. For us those two motions
   fit together naturally.
  On the RL side, we are not trying to build a base model. We are building the learning from experience layer on top. Big frontier labs and RL teams train for broad task distributions. The problem we
  care about is the narrower task distribution a particular company actually faces in production.
  In many enterprise workflows, the objective is sequential and operational: task completion, correct tool use, low escalation, latency, cost, policy adherence, and user acceptance. That is exactly
  where RL and related post-training methods become relevant.
  The practical levers depend on the setup. With closed frontier models, the levers are usually in-context or harness updates and routing. Where customers control the model stack more directly,
  post-training becomes possible as well. So for us the question is not simply whether to use RL, but how to use the right improvement mechanism for the workflow and setup at hand.
  On competition, I think of the landscape in three buckets. First, runtime and memory systems such as Letta. Second, post-training infrastructure such as SkyRL, verl, and similar stacks. Third,
  learning-layer companies that help enterprises optimize deployed systems, such as Applied Compute, Adaptive ML, or smaller players like RunRL.
  We do not need to replace the first two and do not think of them as competitors in the classical sense. In many cases they are complements. We can greatly benefit from each other and the collective
  development of the ecosystem. The broader open RL ecosystem is a tailwind for us because our customers, the enterprises we are in discussion with, future clients are not the deepest ML organizations.
  They are companies already deploying agents, but without a large internal ML team. For them, the value proposition is straightforward: instead of building the improvement loop themselves, they can buy
   that layer as a service. And from our discussions we see demand from such enterprises (e.g. in healthcare, in banking, in cyber security).

  One reason SkyDeck and Pad-13 are particularly attractive to us is that the program would enable closer collaboration with teams in that ecosystem, especially the SkyRL team.
  The simplest way I would describe Aganthos is: we help agentic workflows improve from experience.
